. In Fields of Authority, Jack Lucas provides the first systematic exploration of local special purpose bodies in Ontario. Drawing on extensive research in local and provincial archives, Lucas uses a “policy fields” approach to explain how these local bodies in Ontario have developed from the nineteenth century to the present. A lively and accessible study, Fields of Authority will appeal to readers interested in Canadian political history, urban politics, and urban public policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAdministrative agenciesxHistoryxOntario. 0aAdministrative agencieszOntarioxHistory. 0aLocal governmentxHistoryxOntario. 0aLocal governmentzOntarioxHistory. 0aMunicipal governmentxHistoryxOntario. 0aMunicipal governmentzOntarioxHistory. 0aPublic administrationxHistoryxOntario. 0aPublic administrationzOntarioxHistory. 0aUrban policyxHistoryxOntarioxOntario. 0aUrban policyzOntarioxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Affairs & Administration.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066595640uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751036740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487510367423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487510367.jpg  a978-3-11-066595-6  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles